 {"id":"br-r37-c1-sgjko","title":"parity: time-respecting isomorphism matchers missing","description":"NetworkX exposes TimeRespectingGraphMatcher(G1, G2, temporal_attribute_name, delta) and TimeRespectingDiGraphMatcher(G1, G2, temporal_attribute_name, delta). FrankenNetworkX does not export these classes, leaving temporal VF2 matcher API unavailable. Add wrappers that convert FrankenNetworkX graph objects via _networkx_graph_for_parity and delegate to NetworkX, plus parity tests for signatures and isomorphism mappings on temporal graph/digraph paths.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","assignee":"cod-networkx","created_at":"2026-04-25T09:31:58.717555427Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-25T09:35:34.565138940Z","closed_at":"2026-04-25T09:35:34.563236879Z","close_reason":"Completed in 739ccaa","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-sgnab","title":"parity: _fnx_to_nx converter doesn't preserve adjacency-iteration order","description":"fnx.G.adj[b] = ['a', 'c'] (matches nx for the same input), but after _fnx_to_nx(G), the converted nx graph has adj[b] = ['c', 'a']. The converter iterates fg.edges (canonical-endpoint form) which feeds add_edges_from with (c,b) instead of (b,c) the user added. nx stores adj in user-call order (asymmetric: add_edge(u,v) puts v in adj[u] first, then u in adj[v]). Converted-via-edges order differs from converted-via-adj-iteration order. This silently breaks BFS/DFS-strategy greedy_color, ego_graph, and any algorithm whose result depends on adj iteration. Fix: rewrite _fnx_to_nx to iterate fg.adj[u] in u's insertion order, matching the user-direct-construction adj order.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T12:10:42.092661626Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T12:30:52.781936958Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T12:30:52.779972458Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit f6696a7. _fnx_to_nx now uses per-node-queue topological emit so adj iteration order matches direct nx construction. Self-loops, tuple nodes, and directed graphs all correct. 10 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-sk5be","title":"parity: 3 more all_pairs_* path functions have wrong outer-key iteration order","description":"fnx.all_pairs_bellman_ford_path, fnx.all_pairs_bellman_ford_path_length, and fnx.all_pairs_dijkstra yield outer source keys in arbitrary Rust internal order instead of nx's node-insertion order. Same iteration-order family as br-r37-c1-3dxfn (all_pairs_dijkstra_path). Drop-in code that does 'for source, dists in result: ...' breaks. Fix: iterate via G.nodes() so outer keys come out in node-insertion order.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T10:44:48.953805710Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T10:47:24.742394844Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T10:47:24.740420566Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit e702fc7. all_pairs_bellman_ford_path/_length and all_pairs_dijkstra now yield outer keys in node-insertion order matching nx. 9 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"br-r37-c1-sn6tm","title":"dag_longest_path tie-breaking diverges from nx due to pred-order loss in conversion","description":"fnx.dag_longest_path delegates to nx via _call_networkx_for_parity / _fnx_to_nx, but _fnx_to_nx emits edges via per-node adj iteration (_topo_emit_edges_by_adj) which preserves adj[u] order but scrambles pred[v] order. nx.dag_longest_path's tie-breaking depends on G.pred[v].items() iteration order: max(us, key=lambda x: x[0]) returns the FIRST element with the max key, which is determined by the order of iteration over predecessors.

Repro:
  >>> g = fnx.DiGraph()
  >>> g.add_nodes_from([5,1,3,2,4,6])
  >>> for u,v in [(1,2),(1,3),(2,4),(3,4),(4,5),(4,6)]: g.add_edge(u,v)
  >>> g.pred[4]
  {2: {}, 3: {}}
  >>> fnx.dag_longest_path(g)
  [1, 3, 4, 5]
  >>> nx.dag_longest_path(nx.DiGraph(...same construction...))
  [1, 2, 4, 5]   # tie-break to first-inserted predecessor

After _fnx_to_nx, pred[4] becomes {3:{}, 2:{}} — scrambled because edges() iterates by source-node-order (which puts node 3 before 2 in this case, since the user added [5,1,3,2,4,6] so adj iteration yields 3's edge before 2's).

Fix: implement dag_longest_path natively in fnx using fnx.pred directly, mirroring nx's algorithm but skipping the conversion. This is faster too.","status":"in_progress","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-27T04:16:19.590291609Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-27T04:16:49.501721438Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-t3gkj","title":"parity: jaccard_coefficient / resource_allocation_index / adamic_adar_index have wrong pair order + type drift","description":"Continuation of br-r37-c1-bctxc (preferential_attachment). Three more link-prediction functions diverge from nx: (1) jaccard_coefficient yields pairs in canonical reverse order vs nx's non_edges iteration order. (2) resource_allocation_index returns -0.0 instead of nx's 0 (also pair order differs). (3) adamic_adar_index returns -0.0 instead of nx's 0. Drop-in code matching exact tuples breaks. Fix: delegate all three to nx for pair-order + type parity (Rust impl is just a small score computation per pair, no real perf benefit).","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T12:40:40.016679546Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T12:43:18.132195244Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T12:43:18.130154019Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit d30da51. jaccard/adamic_adar/resource_allocation all delegate to nx for pair-order + zero-score type parity. 14 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-tlrdu","title":"parity: single_source_shortest_path / _length yield dict in wrong (Rust internal) order, nx uses BFS-traversal order","description":"fnx.single_source_shortest_path and fnx.single_source_shortest_path_length yield dict keys in arbitrary Rust internal order. nx returns the dict with keys in BFS-visit order from the source (visiting neighbors in adjacency-dict order at each layer). Drop-in code that iterates 'for tgt, path in single_source_shortest_path(G, src).items(): ...' breaks. Same iteration-order family. Fix: reorder result dict by running a BFS from source in Python, visiting G.adj[u] in iteration order at each layer.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T10:50:54.567910281Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T10:52:58.943215796Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T10:52:58.941209456Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit ae78eb3. single_source_shortest_path / _length now iterate in BFS-visit order matching nx. 15 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-turq0","title":"parity: node_connectivity/edge_connectivity silently return 0 on empty graph, nx raises NetworkXPointlessConcept","description":"fnx.node_connectivity(fnx.empty_graph(0)) returns 0; nx.node_connectivity(nx.empty_graph(0)) raises NetworkXPointlessConcept('Connectivity is undefined for the null graph.'). Same drift in edge_connectivity. Drop-in code that catches NetworkXPointlessConcept to gate empty-graph paths fails to trigger on fnx — silent value masks the contract violation. Fix: add the raise at the top of each wrapper, matching nx's documented behaviour. Single-node case (returns 0 on both) is unchanged.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T07:17:28.519121260Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T07:19:20.086837509Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T07:19:20.084994560Z","close_reason":"Fixed in commit c633959. node_connectivity/edge_connectivity raise NetworkXPointlessConcept on null graph matching nx. 8 parity tests freeze the contract.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
